'''Phillip (Phil) John Lamason''' [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]] [[Medal bar|& Bar]] was an officer of the [[Royal New Zealand Air Force]] (RNZAF) during the [[Second World War]] who rose to prominence as the [[Commanding officer|senior officer]] in charge of 168 [[Allies of World War II|allied]] [[airmen]] taken to [[Buchenwald concentration camp]], Germany, in August 1944.<ref name=AWM>Australian War Memorial (2008). AWM Collection Record: P02988.001: [http://cas.awm.gov.au/photograph/P02988.001 Philip J. Lamason]. Retrieved on 4 January 2009.</ref>

==Early life and RNZAF career== 

Lamason was born in [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]] on 15 September 1918, but was raised in [[Dannevirke]], a small rural community in [[New Zealand]]'s [[North Island]].<ref name=Thompson>Thompson, H. L. (1953). [http://books.google.com/books?id=HSlAOwAACAAJ&dq ''New Zealanders with the Royal Air Force. (Vol. 1)'']. Published by War History Branch, Dept. of Internal Affairs, Wellington. {{OCLC|270919916}}. </ref> Prior to the war, Lamason worked for the Department of Agriculture as a stock inspector. He was described as a tall, good looking man with blue eyes.<ref name=Burgess>Burgess, Colin (1995). [http://books.google.com/books?id=jqKyAAAACAAJ&dq ''Destination Buchenwald'']. Published by Kangaroo Press, Kenthurst NSW. {{OCLC|35019954}}. ISBN: 086417733X.</ref><ref name=Moser/>

Lamason joined the RNZAF in September 1940 and by April 1942, he was a [[pilot officer]] in [[No. 218 Squadron RAF]]. During a bombing raid on [[Pilsen]], the aircraft he was captaining was attacked by an enemy fighter and badly damaged, but managed to return to base.  As a result of his actions, he was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] (DFC) on 15 May 1942. The full citation read:

{{quote|''Air Ministry, 15th May, 1942.''

ROYAL AIR FORCE.

The KING has been graciously pleased to approve the following awards in recognition of gallantry displayed in flying operations against the enemy: <U+2014>

''Distinguished Flying Cross.''

[...]

Pilot Officer Philip John. LAMASON, (N.Z. 403460), Royal New Zealand Air Force, No. 218 Squadron.

One night in April, 1942, this officer was the captain of an aircraft which attacked
Pilsen. During the return flight his aircraft was attacked by an enemy fighter and sustained damage; the hydraulics were shot away and the turret rendered unserviceable, while a fire broke out in the middle of the fuselage. Displaying great presence of mind, Pilot Officer Lamason coolly directed his crew in the emergency and, while 2 of them dealt with the fire, he skilfully outmanoeuvred his attacker and finally shook him off. By his fine airmanship and great devotion to duty, Pilot Officer Lamason was undoubtedly responsible for the safe return of the aircraft and its crew. This officer has completed 21 sorties and he has at all times displayed courage and ability.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=35560|supp=yes|startpage=2121|date=12 May 1942|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref>}}

On 2 June 1943, he was [[Mentioned in Despatches]],<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=36033|supp=yes|startpage=2453|endpage=2457|date=28 May 1943|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> and, having received promotion to acting [[squadron leader]], he was again Mentioned on 14 January 1944.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=36329|startpage=286|endpage=291|date=28 May 1943|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref>  He was awarded a [[medal bar|Bar]] to his DFC on 27 June 1944.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=36584|supp=yes|startpage=3044|date=23 June 1943|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref>

== Buchenwald ==
On 8 June 1944, Lamason was serving as a [[flight (military unit)|flight]] commander in a [[Avro Lancaster|Lancaster]] of [[No. 15 Squadron RAF]], when he was shot down during a raid on railway marshalling yards near [[Paris]].<ref name=Eden/> Lamason recalled: {{quote|On the night of the raid our bomber was spotted by a German fighter, which locked on to it. I decided to turn and fight him. Within seconds an incendiary round hit a wing and caught the fuel tank. I gave the order to bail out as the gas torched. But Robbie, our mid-upper gunner, kept on firing. When he eventually did jump, we no longer had enough height. I saw his parachute open, but too late. He must have died on impact. I pushed the navigator out and managed to jump clear at the last minute.<ref name=Eden>Eden, Richard & Oakes, John (2001). [http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1374126/French-never-forgot-lost-wartime-airman.html French never forgot 'lost' wartime airman]. ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved on 4 January 2009.</ref>}}

[[Image:Phil Lamason2.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Lamason (centre) and another airman playing chess in [[Chevreuse]] with a Frenchwoman whose family hid them for two weeks after they were shot down.]]

Lamason was hidden by the [[French Resistance]] for seven weeks before being captured by the [[Gestapo]] in August after he was betrayed by the French double agent [[Jacques Desoubrie]].<ref name=Thompson/> Many fliers were classified as "Terrorflieger" (terror flier) by the Germans, and were not given a trial. The [[Federal Foreign Office (Germany)|German Foreign Office]] decided that captured enemy airmen should not be given the legal status of [[prisoner of war]] (POWs) but should instead be treated as criminals and spies.<ref name=Canada>Veterans Affairs Canada (2006). [http://www.vac-acc.gc.ca/remembers/sub.cfm?source=history/secondwar/fact_sheets/pow ''Prisoners of War in the Second World War'']. Retrieved on 6 January 2009.</ref><ref name=USAF>National Museum of the USAF (2008). [http://www.nationalmuseum.af.mil/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=1575 ''Fact Sheets: Allied Victims of the Holocaust'']. Retrieved on 5 January 2009.</ref> Consequently, Lamason was amongst 168 allied airmen from [[Great Britain]], [[United States]], [[Australia]], [[Canada]] and New Zealand,<ref name=Canada/> who were taken by train from [[Fresnes Prison]] outside Paris, to [[Buchenwald concentration camp]] and arrived there on 20 August 1944.<ref name=AWM/><ref name=Burgess/><ref name=Lambert>Lambert, Max (2005). [http://books.google.com/books?id=uOJxHAAACAAJ&dq ''Night After Night: New Zealanders in Bomber Command'']. Published by Harper Collins, Auckland. {{OCLC|238569316}}. ISBN: 1869505425.</ref> 

Buchenwald was a [[Nazi concentration camps|labor camp]] of about 60,000 inmates of mainly [[Russians|Russian]] POWs, but also common criminals, religious prisoners (including [[Jews]]), and various [[political prisoners]] from [[Germany]], [[France]], [[Poland]], and [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref name=Crocker>Crocker, Brandon (2008). [http://spectator.org/archives/2004/06/04/an-american-in-buchenwald An American in Buchenwald]. ''The American Spectator''. Retrieved on 4 January 2009.</ref> Upon arrival, Lamason, as ranking officer, demanded an interview with the [[commandant]], which he was granted. He insisted that the airmen be treated as POWs under the [[Geneva Conventions]] and be sent to a [[Prisoner-of-war camp|POW camp]]. The commandant agreed that their arrival at Buchenwald was a "mistake" but they remained there anyway.<ref name=Crocker/> The airmen were given the same poor treatment and beatings as the other inmates.<ref name=USAF/> For the first three weeks at Buchenwald, the prisoners were totally shaven, denied shoes and forced to sleep outside without shelter.<ref name=Canada/>

After their first meal, Lamason stepped forward and stated: {{quote|Gentlemen, we have ourselves in a very fine fix indeed. The goons have completely violated the Geneva Convention and are treating us as common thieves and criminals. However, we are soldiers. From this time on, we will also conduct ourselves as our training has taught us and as our countries would expect from us. We will march as a unit to roll call and we will follow all reasonable commands as a single unit.<ref name=Moser>Moser, Joe (2008). [http://buchenwaldflyboy.wordpress.com/chapter-8-buchenwald/ Buchenwald Flyboy: Chapter 8]. Retrieved on 4 January 2009.</ref>}}

{|class="wikitable" align="right"
|Nationalities of the 168 airmen<ref>[http://bulk.resource.org/gpo.gov/bills/105/hc95ih.txt.pdf 105th Congress] (1997). Recognizing and commending American airmen held as political prisonersat the Buchenwald concentration camp. Retrieved on 11 January 2009.</ref><ref>Stein, Harry (2004, p. 171). [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=d7WlV23kNoUC ''Buchenwald Concentration Camp 1937-1945'']. Published by Wallstein Verlag. {{OCLC|61263627}}. ISBN: 3892446954</ref>
|-
|{{Flagicon|US}} 82 American
|-
|{{Flagicon|UK}} 48 British
|-
|{{Flagicon|Canada|1921}} 26 Canadian
|-
|{{flagicon|Australia}} 9 Australian
|-
