Lamason proceeded to organise the airmen into groups by nationality and appointed a Commanding Officer within each group. Lamason did not do this just to improve their morale but because he also saw it as his responsibility to carry on his war duties despite the adverse circumstances.<ref name=Moser/> Lamason's leadership boosted the airmen's spirits and gave them hope while instilling a level of discipline and bearing.<ref name=Lambert/><ref name=Hope/> One of the first assignments Lamason gave was to mount a guard detail, both day and night, to prevent pilfering by other inmates, which had begun during their first night at camp.<ref name=Burgess/>

For the next six weeks, Lamason negotiated with the German camp authorities, but his requests to have the airmen transferred to proper POW camps were denied.<ref name=Thompson/><ref name=AWM/> One captured British airman, [[Pilot Officer]] S.A. Spierenburg, was a [[Dutch people|Dutchman]] flying for the [[Royal Air Force]].<ref>Air War Web Portal (2008). [http://www.airwarweb.net/dutch_raf.php Dutch Pilots in RAF Service: S.A. Spierenburg]. Retrieved on 24 March 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.lostbombers.co.uk/bomber.php?id=9658 Lancaster ND921 Information] (2009). ''Lost Bombers During World War II''. Retrieved on 24 March 2009.</ref> Spierenburg, who spoke fluent [[German language|German]], regularly acted as an [[Interpreting|interpretor]] for Lamason when he negotiated with the camp authorities.<ref name=Burgess/>

Most airmen doubted they would ever get out of Buchenwald because their documents were stamped with the acronym "DIKAL" (Darf in kein anderes Lager), or "not to be transferred to another camp".<ref name=Burgess/><ref name=Bard/> At great risk, Lamason secretly got word out to the German [[Luftwaffe]] of their captivity at the camp.<ref name=Hope/><ref name=Herald>[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=10119086 Unsung heroes of the bombing war] (2005). ''The New Zealand Herald''. Retrieved on 13 January 2009.</ref> Lamason understood that the Luftwaffe would be sympathetic to their predicament, as they would not want their captured men treated in the same way; he also knew that the Luftwaffe had the political connections to get the airmen transferred to a POW camp.<ref name=Burgess/><ref name=Herald /> Eventually, his persistence paid off and on the night of 19 October, 156 of the 168 airmen, including Lamason, were transferred from Buchenwald to [[Stalag Luft III]] by the Luftwaffe.<ref name=Canada/><ref name=USAF/> Unknown to all except Lamason, their [[Capital punishment|execution]] had been scheduled for 26 October, had they remained at Buchenwald.<ref name=Bard>Bard, Mitchell (2004). [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=8XexaFm8PuAC ''The Complete Idiot's Guide to World War II'']. Published by Alpha Books. {{OCLC|43803305}}. ISBN: 1592572049.</ref><ref name=Hope>Hope, Derek (2008). [http://www.airforce.mil.nz/operations/airforce-news/93/flier-remembered.htm A flier is remembered]. ''Royal New Zealand Air Force''. Retrieved on 6 January 2009.</ref><ref name=Herald/> The twelve remaining POWs were too sick to travel and remained at Buchenwald. Two subsequently died from sickness and the other ten were transported to Stalag Luft III several days later.<ref name=USAF/> In late January 1945, all Stalag Luft III POWs were [[The March (1945)|forced marched]] to [[Stalag III-A|Luckenwalde]], where they remained until liberated by the [[Soviet Union|Russian]] army at the [[End of World War II in Europe|end of the war in Europe]].<ref>Lambly, Annette (2008). [http://www.northernadvocate.co.nz/storyprint.cfm?storyID=3771348 Secret story finally told]. ''Whangarei Northern Advocate''. Retrieved on 17 February 2009.</ref><ref>Nichol, John and Rennell, Tony (2002). [http://books.google.com/books?id=d3YxGQAACAAJ&dq|''The last escape: the untold story of allied prisoners of war in Germany 1944 - 1945'']. Published by Viking Books, London. {{OCLC|231974289}}. ISBN: 0670910945.</ref>

Many airmen credit their survival at Buchenwald to the leadership and determination of Lamason.<ref name=Thompson/><ref name=Lambert/> Captured pilot, Stratton Appleman, stated that "they were very fortunate to have Lamason as their leader".<ref name=Burgess/> Another airman, Joe Moser, stated that Lamason was a great leader who he would have been glad to follow anywhere he asked.<ref name=Moser/>

== Aftermath ==
Following their liberation and return to England, Lamason was asked to consider commanding one of the [[Okinawa]] squadrons for the final [[Operation Downfall|attack on Japan]]. However, the RNZAF refused and Lamason returned to New Zealand, arriving there the day after the [[Nuclear weapon|atomic bomb]] was dropped on [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|Hiroshima]].<ref name=Burgess/> After the war, Lamason was discharged from the air force on 16 December 1945.<ref>Hanson, C. M. (2001). [http://books.google.com/books?id=ehhNAQAACAAJ&dq ''By such deeds: honours and awards in the Royal New Zealand Air Force, 1923-1999'']. Published by Volplane Press, Christchurch. {{OCLC|155402329}}. ISBN: 9780473073015.</ref> He returned to Dannevirke and became a [[farmer]] until his retirement. In April 2005, Lamason, then 86, recollected the events of Buchenwald on [[Television New Zealand|TV New Zealand]].<ref>[http://tvnz.co.nz/view/news_national_story_skin/518820 Ex-RAF bomber remembers WWII] (2005). ''Television New Zealand Limited''. Retrieved on 15 February 2009.</ref>

